04229nam a2200577Ia 9780292767362DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20142014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927673627 a10.7560/7581242doi  a(DE-B1597)587298  a(OCoLC)1286806629  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a863/.641 aWilliams, Raymond Leslie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMario Vargas Llosa :bA Life of Writing /cRaymond Leslie Williams. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart I. An Intellectual Biography -- tPart II. A Novelist for the Twenty-First Century -- tPart III. Rereading Vargas Llosa -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix 1. An Interview with Mario Vargas Llosa -- tAppendix 2. Fiction of Mario Vargas Llosa -- tAppendix 3. Selected Essays of Mario Vargas Llosa -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAwarded the Nobel Prize in 2010 at the age of seventy-four, Peruvian writer Mario Vargas Llosa has held pivotal roles in the evolution and revolutions of modern Latin American literature. Perhaps surprisingly, no complete history of Vargas Llosa’s works, placed in biographical and historical context, has been published—until now. A masterwork from one of America’s most revered scholars of Latin American fiction, Mario Vargas Llosa: A Life of Writing provides a critical overview of Vargas Llosa’s numerous novels while reinvigorating debates regarding conventional interpretations of the work. Weaving analysis with discussions of the writer’s political commentary, Raymond Leslie Williams traces the author’s youthful identity as a leftist student of the 1960s to a repudiation of some of his earlier ideas beginning in the 1980s. Providing a unique perspective on the complexity, nuance, and scope of Vargas Llosa’s lauded early novels and on his passionate support of indigenous populations in his homeland, Williams then turns his eye to the recent works, which serve as a bridge between the legacies of the Boom and the diverse array of contemporary Latin American fiction writers at work today. In addition, Williams provides a detailed description of Vargas Llosa’s traumatic childhood and its impact on him—seen particularly in his lifelong disdain for authority figures—as well as of the authors who influenced his approach, from Faulkner to Flaubert. Culminating in reflections drawn from Williams’s formal interviews and casual conversations with the author at key phases of both men’s careers, this is a landmark publication that will spark new lines of inquiry into an intricate body of work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074533740uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75812440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767362423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767362/original  a978-3-11-074533-7  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles